# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clip-model
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:clip-model/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The CLIP method trains a pair of models contrastively.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] One model takes in a piece of text as input and outputs a single vector representing its semantic content.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The other model takes in an image and similarly outputs a single vector representing its visual content.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The models are trained so that the vectors corresponding to semantically similar text-image pairs are close together in the shared vector space, while those corresponding to dissimilar pairs are far apart.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] To train a pair of CLIP models, one would start by preparing a large dataset of image-caption pairs.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] During training, the models are presented with batches of N image-caption pairs.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Two vectors are considered "similar" if their dot product is large.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For each image, the similarity scores with the N texts are converted by a softmax into a probability distribution over which text is the matching one.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Cross-entropy is then computed against the one-hot target that assigns probability 1 to the correct text; the same calculation is also performed in the text-to-image direction.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The parameter $T>0$ is the temperature, which is parameterized in the original CLIP model as $T=e^{-\tau }$ where $\tau \in \mathbb {R}$ is a learned parameter.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, Sigmoid CLIP (SigLIP) proposes the following loss function: $L={\frac {1}{N}}\sum _{i,j\in 1:N}f((2\delta _{i,j}-1)(e^{\tau }w_{i}\cdot v_{j}+b))$ where $f(x)=\ln(1+e^{-x})$ is the negative log sigmoid loss, and the Dirac delta symbol $\delta _{i,j}$ is 1 if $i=j$ else 0.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] While the original model was developed by OpenAI, subsequent models have been trained by other organizations as well.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The image encoding models used in CLIP are typically vision transformers (ViT).
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The naming convention for these models often reflects the specific ViT architecture used.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For instance, "ViT-L/14" means a "vision transformer large" (compared to other models in the same series) with a patch size of 14, meaning that the image is divided into 14-by-14 pixel patches before being processed by the transformer.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The size indicator ranges from B, L, H, G (base, large, huge, giant), in that order.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Other than ViT, the image model is typically a convolutional neural network, such as ResNet (in the original series by OpenAI), or ConvNeXt (in the OpenCLIP model series by LAION).
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Since the output vectors of the image model and the text model must have exactly the same length, both the image model and the text model have fixed-length vector outputs, which in the original report is called "embedding dimension".
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, in the original OpenAI model, the ResNet models have embedding dimensions ranging from 512 to 1024, and for the ViTs, from 512 to 768.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Its implementation of ViT was the same as the original one, with one modification: after position embeddings are added to the initial patch embeddings, there is a LayerNorm.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] ALIGN a model with similar capabilities, trained by researchers from Google used EfficientNet, a kind of convolutional neural network.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The text encoding models used in CLIP are typically transformers.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In the original OpenAI report, they reported using a Transformer (63M-parameter, 12-layer, 512-wide, 8 attention heads) with lower-cased byte pair encoding (BPE) with 49152 vocabulary size.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Context length was capped at 76 for efficiency.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Like GPT, it was decoder-only, with only causally-masked self-attention.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Like BERT, the text sequence is bracketed by two special tokens `[SOS]` and `[EOS]` ("start of sequence" and "end of sequence").
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Take the activations of the highest layer of the transformer on the `[EOS]`, apply LayerNorm, then a final linear map.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] This is the text encoding of the input sequence.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The final linear map has output dimension equal to the embedding dimension of whatever image encoder it is paired with.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] These models all had context length 77 and vocabulary size 49408.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The CLIP models released by OpenAI were trained on a dataset called "WebImageText" (WIT) containing 400 million pairs of images and their corresponding captions scraped from the internet.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The total number of words in this dataset is similar in scale to the WebText dataset used for training GPT-2, which contains about 40 gigabytes of text data.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The dataset contains 500,000 text-queries, with up to 20,000 (image, text) pairs per query.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The text-queries were generated by starting with all words occurring at least 100 times in English Wikipedia, then extended by bigrams with high mutual information, names of all Wikipedia articles above a certain search volume, and WordNet synsets.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The dataset is private and has not been released to the public, and there is no further information on it.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The rationale was that these are the mean and standard deviations of the images in the WebImageText dataset, so this preprocessing step roughly whitens the image tensor.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] ALIGN used over one billion image-text pairs, obtained by extracting images and their alt-tags from online crawling.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The method was described as similar to how the Conceptual Captions dataset was constructed, but instead of complex filtering, they only applied a frequency-based filtering.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] Later models trained by other organizations had published datasets.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, LAION trained OpenCLIP with published datasets LAION-400M, LAION-2B, and DataComp-1B.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In the original OpenAI CLIP report, they reported training 5 ResNet and 3 ViT (ViT-B/32, ViT-B/16, ViT-L/14).
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The largest ResNet model took 18 days to train on 592 V100 GPUs.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The largest ViT model took 12 days on 256 V100 GPUs.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] All ViT models were trained on 224×224 image resolution.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The ViT-L/14 was then boosted to 336×336 resolution by FixRes, resulting in a model.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] They found this was the best-performing model.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In the OpenCLIP series, the ViT-L/14 model was trained on 384 A100 GPUs on the LAION-2B dataset, for 160 epochs for a total of 32B samples seen.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP's cross-modal retrieval enables the alignment of visual and textual data in a shared latent space, allowing users to retrieve images based on text descriptions and vice versa, without the need for explicit image annotations.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In **text-to-image retrieval**, users input descriptive text, and CLIP retrieves images with matching embeddings.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] In **image-to-text retrieval**, images are used to find related text content.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP’s ability to connect visual and textual data has found applications in multimedia search, content discovery, and recommendation systems.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP can perform zero-shot image classification tasks.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] This is achieved by prompting the text encoder with class names and selecting the class whose embedding is closest to the image embedding.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, to classify an image, they compared the embedding of the image with the embedding of the text "A photo of a {class}.", and the {class} that results in the highest dot product is outputted.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] CLIP has been used as a component in multimodal learning.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] For example, during the training of Google DeepMind's Flamingo (2022), the authors trained a CLIP pair, with BERT as the text encoder and NormalizerFree ResNet F6 as the image encoder.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The image encoder of the CLIP pair was taken with parameters frozen and the text encoder was discarded.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-language-image-pretraining] The frozen image encoder was then combined with a frozen Chinchilla language model, by finetuning with some further parameters that connect the two frozen models.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labels are automatically generated labels that a model assigns to unlabeled data based on its own predictions.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] They are widely used in self-supervised and semi-supervised learning, where ground-truth annotations are limited or unavailable.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] By treating predicted labels as surrogate ground truth, learning algorithms can make use of large quantities of unlabeled data in the training process.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labeling also plays an important role in systems that must adapt to concept drift, where the statistical properties of the data change over time.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] In these scenarios, the model may detect that an incoming instance deviates from previously learned behavior.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] The system then generates a classification result for that instance, and this predicted class is used as a pseudo-label for updating or retraining model components that are becoming outdated.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] This approach enables continuous adaptation in dynamic environments without requiring manual annotation.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] In many adaptive learning pipelines, pseudo-labels are chosen when the classifier produces sufficiently confident predictions, reducing the risk of propagating errors.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] These pseudo-labeled instances are then incorporated into training to refresh or evolve the model's understanding of emerging data patterns, particularly when existing components show signs of “aging” due to drift or distributional shifts.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] This strategy reduces reliance on manual labeling while helping maintain long-term model performance.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Autoassociative self-supervised learning is a specific category of self-supervised learning where a neural network is trained to reproduce or reconstruct its own input data.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] In other words, the model is tasked with learning a representation of the data that captures its essential features or structure, allowing it to regenerate the original input.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] The term "autoassociative" comes from the fact that the model is essentially associating the input data with itself.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] This is often achieved using autoencoders, which are a type of neural network architecture used for representation learning.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Autoencoders consist of an *encoder* network that maps the input data to a lower-dimensional representation (latent space), and a *decoder* network that reconstructs the input from this representation.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] The training process involves presenting the model with input data and requiring it to reconstruct the same data as closely as possible.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] The loss function used during training typically penalizes the difference between the original input and the reconstructed output (e.g. mean squared error).
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] By minimizing this reconstruction error, the autoencoder learns a meaningful representation of the data in its latent space.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] For a binary classification task, training data can be divided into positive examples and negative examples.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Positive examples are those that match the target.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] For example, if training a classifier to identify birds, the positive training data would include images that contain birds.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Negative examples would be images that do not.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Contrastive self-supervised learning uses both positive and negative examples.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] The loss function in contrastive learning is used to minimize the distance between positive sample pairs, while maximizing the distance between negative sample pairs.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] An early example uses a pair of 1-dimensional convolutional neural networks to process a pair of images and maximize their agreement.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training (CLIP) allows joint pretraining of a text encoder and an image encoder, such that a matching image-text pair have image encoding vector and text encoding vector that span a small angle (having a large cosine similarity).
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] InfoNCE (Noise-Contrastive Estimation) is a method to optimize two models jointly, based on Noise Contrastive Estimation (NCE).
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Non-contrastive self-supervised learning (NCSSL) uses only positive examples.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Counterintuitively, NCSSL converges on a useful local minimum rather than reaching a trivial solution, with zero loss.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] For the example of binary classification, it would trivially learn to classify each example as positive.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Effective NCSSL requires an extra predictor on the online side that does not back-propagate on the target side.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] A major class of self-supervised learning moves beyond contrastive pairs, instead maximizing the agreement between views while preventing collapse through statistical constraints.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Rooted in Deep Canonical Correlation Analysis (Deep CCA), this approach includes Joint-Embedding Architectures (JEA) like Barlow Twins and VICReg, which enforce covariance constraints to learn invariant representations without negative sampling.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Deep Latent Variable Path Modelling (DLVPM) generalizes this to multimodal systems, using path models to enforce correlation and orthogonality across diverse data types.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] In 2022 Yann LeCun introduced Joint-Embedding Predictive Architectures (JEPA) as a step towards decision making, reasoning, and autonomous human intelligence in machines, including self-improvement through autonomous learning.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Founded in representation learning, LeCun included the concept of a “world model” in JEPA which aims to enable machines to replicate human intellect by providing machines with a concept for the world in which they exist.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Unlike autoencoders, JEPAs operate entirely in latent space, avoiding pixel-level noise to focus on semantic structure.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Rather than just learning invariance, JEPAs learn by predicting masked latent representations from visible context.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] JEPA has been applied to domains such as image analysis, audio processing, and motion in images and video.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] SSL belongs to supervised learning methods insofar as the goal is to generate a classified output from the input.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] At the same time, however, it does not require the explicit use of labeled input-output pairs.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Instead, correlations, metadata embedded in the data, or domain knowledge present in the input are implicitly and autonomously extracted from the data.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] These supervisory signals, extracted from the data, can then be used for training.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] SSL is similar to unsupervised learning in that it does not require labels in the sample data.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Unlike unsupervised learning, however, learning is not done using inherent data structures.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Semi-supervised learning combines supervised and unsupervised learning, requiring only a small portion of the learning data be labeled.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] In transfer learning, a model designed for one task is reused on a different task.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Training an autoencoder intrinsically constitutes a self-supervised process, because the output pattern needs to become an optimal reconstruction of the input pattern itself.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] However, in current jargon, the term 'self-supervised' often refers to tasks based on a pretext-task training setup.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] This involves the (human) design of such pretext task(s), unlike the case of fully self-contained autoencoder training.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] In reinforcement learning, self-supervising learning from a combination of losses can create abstract representations where only the most important information about the state are kept in a compressed way.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning is particularly suitable for speech recognition.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] For example, Facebook developed *wav2vec*, a self-supervised algorithm, to perform speech recognition using two deep convolutional neural networks that build on each other.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Google's Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) model is used to better understand the context of search queries.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] OpenAI's GPT-3 is an autoregressive language model that can be used in language processing.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] It can be used to translate texts or answer questions, among other things.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] The Yarowsky algorithm is an example of self-supervised learning in natural language processing.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] From a small number of labeled examples, it learns to predict which word sense of a polysemous word is being used at a given point in text.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] DirectPred is a NCSSL that directly sets the predictor weights instead of learning it via typical gradient descent.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Self-GenomeNet is an example of self-supervised learning in genomics.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] SelfAPR is an example of self-supervised learning applied to automated program repair, where a neural model is trained on perturbations of a previous version of the program under repair and uses test execution diagnostics to synthesize patches.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning continues to gain prominence as a new approach across diverse fields.
[src:clip-model/contrastive-learning] Its ability to leverage unlabeled data effectively opens new possibilities for advancement in machine learning, especially in data-driven application domains.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Multimodal learning was proposed in 2011 at the beginning of the deep learning period.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Large multimodal models, such as Google Gemini and GPT-4o, have become increasingly popular since 2023, enabling increased versatility and a broader understanding of real-world phenomena.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Data usually comes with different modalities which carry different information.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] For example, it is very common to caption an image to convey the information not presented in the image itself.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Similarly, sometimes it is more straightforward to use an image to describe information which may not be obvious from text.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] As a result, if different words appear in similar images, then these words likely describe the same thing.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Conversely, if a word is used to describe seemingly dissimilar images, then these images may represent the same object.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Thus, in cases dealing with multi-modal data, it is important to use a model which is able to jointly represent the information such that the model can capture the combined information from different modalities.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Models such as CLIP (Contrastive Language–Image Pretraining) learn joint representations of images and text by optimizing contrastive objectives, allowing the model to match images with their corresponding textual descriptions.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] A Boltzmann machine is a type of stochastic neural network invented by Geoffrey Hinton and Terry Sejnowski in 1985.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Boltzmann machines can be seen as the stochastic, generative counterpart of Hopfield nets.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] They are named after the Boltzmann distribution in statistical mechanics.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] The units in Boltzmann machines are divided into two groups: visible units and hidden units.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Each unit is like a neuron with a binary output that represents whether it is activated or not.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] General Boltzmann machines allow connection between any units.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] However, learning is impractical using general Boltzmann Machines because the computational time is exponential to the size of the machine.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] A more efficient architecture is called restricted Boltzmann machine where connection is only allowed between hidden unit and visible unit, which is described in the next section.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] Multimodal deep Boltzmann machines can process and learn from different types of information, such as images and text, simultaneously.
[src:clip-model/multimodal-learning] This can notably be done by having a separate deep Boltzmann machine for each modality, for example one for images and one for text, joined at an additional top hidden layer.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] In natural language processing, a **word embedding** is a representation of a word.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes the meaning of the word in such a way that the words that are closer in the vector space are expected to be similar in meaning.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Word embeddings can be obtained using language modeling and feature learning techniques, where words or phrases from the vocabulary are mapped to vectors of real numbers.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Methods to generate this mapping include neural networks, dimensionality reduction on the word co-occurrence matrix, probabilistic models, explainable knowledge base method, and explicit representation in terms of the context in which words appear.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Word and phrase embeddings, when used as the underlying input representation, have been shown to boost the performance in NLP tasks such as syntactic parsing and sentiment analysis.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] In distributional semantics, a quantitative methodological approach for understanding meaning in observed language, word embeddings or semantic feature space models have been used as a knowledge representation for some time.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Such models aim to quantify and categorize semantic similarities between linguistic items based on their distributional properties in large samples of language data.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The underlying idea that "a word is characterized by the company it keeps" was proposed in a 1957 article by John Rupert Firth, but also has roots in the contemporaneous work on search systems and in cognitive psychology.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The first generation of semantic space models is the vector space model for information retrieval.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Such vector space models for words and their distributional data implemented in their simplest form results in a very sparse vector space of high dimensionality (cf. curse of dimensionality).
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Reducing the number of dimensions using linear algebraic methods such as singular value decomposition then led to the introduction of latent semantic analysis in the late 1980s and the random indexing approach for collecting word co-occurrence contexts.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] In 2000, Bengio et al. provided in a series of papers titled "Neural probabilistic language models" to reduce the high dimensionality of word representations in contexts by "learning a distributed representation for words".
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] A study published in NeurIPS (NIPS) 2002 introduced the use of both word and document embeddings applying the method of kernel CCA to bilingual (and multi-lingual) corpora, also providing an early example of self-supervised learning of word embeddings.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Word embeddings come in two different styles, one in which words are expressed as vectors of co-occurring words, and another in which words are expressed as vectors of linguistic contexts in which the words occur; these different styles are studied in Lavelli et al., 2004.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Roweis and Saul published in *Science* how to use "locally linear embedding" (LLE) to discover representations of high dimensional data structures.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Most new word embedding techniques after about 2005 rely on a neural network architecture instead of more probabilistic and algebraic models, after foundational work done by Yoshua Bengio and colleagues.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The approach has been adopted by many research groups after theoretical advances in 2010 had been made on the quality of vectors and the training speed of the model, as well as after hardware advances allowed for a broader parameter space to be explored profitably.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] In 2013, a team at Google led by Tomas Mikolov created word2vec, a word embedding toolkit that can train vector space models faster than previous approaches.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The word2vec approach has been widely used in experimentation and was instrumental in raising interest for word embeddings as a technology, moving the research strand out of specialised research into broader experimentation and eventually paving the way for practical application.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Historically, one of the main limitations of static word embeddings or word vector space models is that words with multiple meanings are conflated into a single representation (a single vector in the semantic space).
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] In other words, polysemy and homonymy are not handled properly.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] For example, in the sentence "The club I tried yesterday was great!", it is not clear if the term *club* is related to the word sense of a *club sandwich*, *clubhouse*, *golf club*, or any other sense that *club* might have.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The necessity to accommodate multiple meanings per word in different vectors (multi-sense embeddings) is the motivation for several contributions in NLP to split single-sense embeddings into multi-sense ones.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Most approaches that produce multi-sense embeddings can be divided into two main categories for their word sense representation, i.e., unsupervised and knowledge-based.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Based on word2vec skip-gram, Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (MSSG) performs word-sense discrimination and embedding simultaneously, improving its training time, while assuming a specific number of senses for each word.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] In the Non-Parametric Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (NP-MSSG) this number can vary depending on each word.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Once the words are disambiguated, they can be used in a standard word embeddings technique, so multi-sense embeddings are produced.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] MSSA architecture allows the disambiguation and annotation process to be performed recurrently in a self-improving manner.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The use of multi-sense embeddings is known to improve performance in several NLP tasks, such as part-of-speech tagging, semantic relation identification, semantic relatedness, named entity recognition and sentiment analysis.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] As of the late 2010s, contextually-meaningful embeddings such as ELMo and BERT have been developed.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Unlike static word embeddings, these embeddings are at the token-level, in that each occurrence of a word has its own embedding.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] These embeddings better reflect the multi-sense nature of words, because occurrences of a word in similar contexts are situated in similar regions of BERT's embedding space.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Word embeddings for *n-*grams in biological sequences (e.g.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] DNA, RNA, and proteins) for bioinformatics applications have been proposed by Asgari and Mofrad.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Named bio-vectors (BioVec) to refer to biological sequences in general with protein-vectors (ProtVec) for proteins (amino-acid sequences) and gene-vectors (GeneVec) for gene sequences, this representation can be widely used in applications of deep learning in proteomics and genomics.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The results presented by Asgari and Mofrad suggest that BioVectors can characterize biological sequences in terms of biochemical and biophysical interpretations of the underlying patterns.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Word embeddings with applications in game design have been proposed by Rabii and Cook as a way to discover emergent gameplay using logs of gameplay data.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The process requires transcribing actions that occur during a game within a formal language and then using the resulting text to create word embeddings.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The results presented by Rabii and Cook suggest that the resulting vectors can capture expert knowledge about games like chess that are not explicitly stated in the game's rules.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] The idea has been extended to embeddings of entire sentences or even documents, e.g. in the form of the thought vectors concept.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] In 2015, some researchers suggested "skip-thought vectors" as a means to improve the quality of machine translation.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] A more recent and popular approach for representing sentences is Sentence-BERT, or SentenceTransformers, which modifies pre-trained BERT with the use of siamese and triplet network structures.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Software for training and using word embeddings includes Tomáš Mikolov's Word2vec, Stanford University's GloVe, GN-GloVe, Flair embeddings, AllenNLP's ELMo, BERT, fastText, Gensim, Indra, and Deeplearning4j.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Principal Component Analysis (PCA), Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP), and T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbour Embedding (t-SNE) are used to reduce the dimensionality of word vector spaces and visualize word embeddings and clusters.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] For instance, the fastText is also used to calculate word embeddings for text corpora in Sketch Engine that are available online.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Word embeddings may contain the biases and stereotypes contained in the trained dataset, as Bolukbasi et al. points out in the 2016 paper "Man is to Computer Programmer as Woman is to Homemaker?
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] For example, one of the analogies generated using the aforementioned word embedding is "man is to computer programmer as woman is to homemaker".
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Research done by Jieyu Zhao et al. shows that the applications of these trained word embeddings without careful oversight likely perpetuates existing bias in society, which is introduced through unaltered training data.
[src:clip-model/word-embedding] Furthermore, word embeddings can even amplify these biases.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] Zero-shot methods generally work by associating observed and non-observed classes through auxiliary information that encodes observable distinguishing properties of objects.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] This problem is widely studied in computer vision, natural language processing, and machine perception.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] The first paper on zero-shot learning in natural language processing appeared in a 2008 paper by Chang, Ratinov, Roth, and Srikumar, at the AAAI'08, but the name given to the learning paradigm there was *dataless classification*.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] The first paper on zero-shot learning in computer vision appeared at the same conference, under the name *zero-data learning*.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] The term *zero-shot learning* itself first appeared in the literature in a 2009 paper from Palatucci, Hinton, Pomerleau, and Mitchell at NIPS'09.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] This terminology was repeated later in another computer vision paper and the term *zero-shot learning* caught on, as a take-off on *one-shot learning* that was introduced in computer vision years earlier.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] In computer vision, zero-shot learning models learned parameters for seen classes along with their class representations and rely on representational similarity among class labels so that, during inference, instances can be classified into new classes.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] In natural language processing, the key technical direction developed builds on the ability to "understand the labels"—represent the labels in the same semantic space as that of the documents to be classified.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] This supports the classification of a *single example* without observing any annotated data, the purest form of zero-shot classification.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] The original paper made use of the Explicit Semantic Analysis (ESA) representation but later papers made use of other representations, including dense representations.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] This approach was also extended to multilingual domains, fine entity typing and other problems.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] Moreover, beyond relying solely on representations, the computational approach has been extended to depend on transfer from other tasks, such as textual entailment and question answering.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] The original paper also points out that, beyond the ability to classify a single example, when a collection of examples is given, with the assumption that they come from the same distribution, it is possible to bootstrap the performance in a semi-supervised like manner (or transductive learning).
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] Unlike standard generalization in machine learning, where classifiers are expected to correctly classify new samples to classes they have already observed during training, in ZSL, no samples from the classes have been given during training the classifier.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] It can therefore be viewed as an extreme case of domain adaptation.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] Naturally, some form of auxiliary information has to be given about these zero-shot classes, and this type of information can be of several types.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] The above ZSL setup assumes that at test time, only zero-shot samples are given, namely, samples from new unseen classes.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] In generalized zero-shot learning, samples from both new and known classes may appear at test time.
[src:clip-model/zero-shot-learning] This poses new challenges for classifiers at test time, because it is very challenging to estimate if a given sample is new or known.
